I want to start this review by admiring the ambiance Gary Danko has to offer. Upon entry, my guests and I were greeted by the hosts and seated promptly. Their menu offers a variety of dishes, 3+ course meals. The night of our dinner, Gary Danko was featuring the Truffle Tasting menu. The options were endless! The truffled risotto with rock shrimp, dungeness crab, shimeji mushrooms and root vegetables was my favorite of the evening. It had rich flavors all around, and the crab and shrimp really complemented the dish. My second favorite entree was the branzini, the emulsified saffron-orange added an artistic touch to this dish as it was very presentable. The fish was crispy on the outside, while tender and flavorful within. I finished my meal with the recommended lemon soufflé cake, which was paired with a refreshing raspberry sorbet. My guests enjoyed the venison, lamb, and filet. I sampled the lamb and it was delicious! I found the blend of medoojl dates and farroto quite interesting (and tasty, nonetheless). In addition to the lemon soufflé cake, we ordered the chocolate and pumpkin soufflé. Both were exceptional, although I don't think I would overindulge. Their wine list definitely deserves a look over. I really enjoyed the french chardonnay over dinner. Gary Danko is a fine American restaurant. It presents its guests with hospitality and a traditional dining experience.

Great meal :) drinks are pretty pricy. I loved the tuna appetizer and the scallops and my husband loved the crab salad and filet of beef. The strawberry soufflé was just ok but the cheese course was very good.

Gary Danko is one of my favorite restaurants in San Francisco. If I had more money, I would come here all the time. Truthfully though, as far as nicer Michelin starred restaurants in the Bay Area go, Gary Danko is really good value. The service is impeccable as well. At Gary Danko, you choose how many courses you'd like and pay accordingly (3 Courses: $87, 4 Courses: $106, 5 Courses: $124). In my opinion, the prices are all pretty reasonable since the portion sizes are on the more generous side too. In addition to having the flexibility of choosing how many courses you want, you get the flexibility of choosing what the courses are as well. If your heart desires that all 5 of your courses come from their Fish and Seafood section, your heart will get what it wants. I do need to advise that you reserve one of your 3+ courses to be the seared foie gras. Their seared foie gras is not only delicious but also quite a good size. Pretty much everything is delicious though, so you can't really go wrong.

Finally got to see what this hype is all about! I came here for dinner on my birthday and the dining experience was great. I think I might had my expectations set higher based on what I've heard from others who have dined at Gary Danko. Don't get me wrong, the food is fantastic but I just didn't feel like it's as hyped up as others make it sound. The staff was great and gave recommendations on choices that weren't just popular but ones they felt would be suitable based on what I usually eat at other places. Their soup of the day was delicious, I believe it was a mushroom soup. It has been a while since I've been here so I can't specifically remember all the choices I ordered during the four course meal. Hopefully my pictures do it justice and others get temped to try what I tried. I never got disappointed by the dishes I ordered. The dessert platter was out of this world, not only did the chef send out a dessert sampler, we also had the dessert choices we ordered. It was dessert overload. At the end of dinner, you receive a yummy cake from the chef.

Celebrated my girlfriends birthday here last week. Was surprised by their service and their food! We sat at the bar our bartender was very helpful. Overall, I would definitely say that it was worth every penny. We were very impressed we came back the very next day.

Gary Danko has been on my to-try list forever, but alas, I kept postponing it for all the exciting new restaurants cropping up. First world dining problems. When I finally visited, I went in with expectations of an old school, but strong fine dining menu, and stellar service. The food met my expectations for 1 Michelin star, but the service fell short. FOOD: Gary Danko offers a tasting menu or a pick-your-own 3, 4, or 5 course menu. Our table went the custom route, and they even let us choose varying course lengths. Half our table skipped dessert, and one got an extra entree, but the timing was such that it wasn't awkward. Oysters w/ Caviar - A staple dish. Better than I expected. Creamy, decadent, with a strong oyster taste. Seared Sea Scallops - Perfectly cooked, tender scallops. Nice contrast with the crunchy lotus root chip. Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb - Not the best plating, but the lamb was juicy and had delicate flavor. Went well with the polenta. Coconut Thai Curry w/ Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Shiitake - This was one loaded dish with at least two of each seafood ingredient. The curry was delicious, but I'm easy to please with Thai curry. The plating was also messy, but it evoked a rustic feel. Cheese Course - This was my favorite course by far. You pick from a glorious cheese cart display! On top of that, they had a goat cheese called "Adrienne." Match made in heaven? We chose four cheeses each, served with grapes and bread. Of the four, I actually liked Adrienne the least! But that's because the other three (including the best blue cheese I've had) were outstanding. Mmm mmm. Roasted Pear over Gingerbread w/ Nutmeg Ice Cream - I loved the flavors of the nutmeg ice cream and the gingerbread. The pear wasn't bad, but it didn't add to the other components. SERVICE: Gary Danko service is legendary and many would say that it outshines the food. Perhaps we came on an off-night, because I was seeing cracks in the seemingly perfect service. Water took just a tad longer to be refilled, my empty cocktail glass stayed on my table for 20+ min, servers waited too long to check-in, etc. The killer was when we just got into our car at the valet and the server came running out, check in hand. "I gave you the wrong check!" We asked if it was more or less. Of course we owed more. The waiter even said "Yeah, I'm really glad I caught up with you guys." Tacky tacky. AMBIANCE: Upscale, white glove atmosphere. Many male diners wearing suit jackets. Very dark inside, even when it was sunny outside. Other notes: -Total dinner time was just under 3 hours. -Parting gift was a very moist and tasty pumpkin cheese cream muffin. -Some of the nicest restaurant bathrooms I've seen. Absurdly soft toilet paper.

This place was absolutely AMAZING!! The hostess and wait staff are on it and definitely take pride in their job and it shows. The food . . . Delicious, delicious, delicious. One of my favorite things was the Rolls Royce of cheese carts. My mouth is watering just thinking about going back here.

Expensive$$$$... But ooohhSooo... GOOD! Worth it, worth it. Caviars and blinis is a must order. Buckwheat blinis was excellent! Had 5 course dinner and everything came out perfecto! The service was beyond expectations . So i will be back for more. It was my first time and it won't be my last so hopefully they have a changing menu so I can try new dishes.

We popped in on Thursday underdressed (I was mad at my husband he made me feel that way), and had an amazing dinner!!! Staff was so warm and welcoming! Thank you! Bar staff, cocktails, food, cheese, food, everything. Amazing! Best meal in SF!!

Numerous reviews stating the obvious - great food & wine choices, great service, great ambiance, and great location. Let me reconfirm and reinforce the obvious. Food - as a diner you have many options. Set tasting menu, 3-4-5 course options and the entire party can pick and choose as they please without all being forced to select the same courses. Wine parings also to match each individual course if you choose so. For appetizer we loved the Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar and Seared Foie Gras. For seafood, go with the Sea Bass and for poultry, the Stuffed Quail. The Bison, is less fatty than beef, thus you will need to go medium rare and be ready to work the mandible. The Grand Marnier Soufflé is fluffy, rich, baked goodness with two sauces and scoop of ice cream. Baked good packed for the next morning or for a late night snack. Service - professional, knowledgable, un-pretentious service. Our Wait Team consisted of Sam, Jeremiah (Sommelier), William, and Neal. Sam and William described the menu and dining format. They also suggest plate presentation if you order multiple items in the same category. Usually from lighter to heavier fare. Jeremiah described each wine paring with passion and also helped recharge a cell phone when my son mentioned his photo shooting phone was almost out of power. The wine parings were described in great detail with each course and the pours were generous. Neal supplied bread constantly, cleared plates, and snapped pictures for us. All around great service and the staff is perceptive as to when patrons want minimal to additional dialog. Ambiance - beautiful Asian themed setting with orchids and cherry blossoms interspersed throughout the restaurant. Tables are a bit close together but not to the point where other diners' conversations are disruptive. Place was constantly packed - a good sign. Location - a block away from Ghiradelli Square, walking distance to some of the best views of San Francisco Bay, valet parking, and free street parking after 6pm if you have time to look for a space. Gary Danko is a great three-hour value.

My first Michelin star experience, and it sure was a good one. Thank you BF for surprising me and making a reservation for our anniversary. I was truly surprised not only by our reservation, but also the presentation and execution of the food, and of course, world class service. Coming in on a friday night, we made a reservation, showed up early and was seated promptly. FYI: Valet is approx $20. We were able to find street parking 2 blocks away..so if you don't mind walking. If you haven't read the copious amount of reviews, Gary Danko works like this: you cane either choose a prefix menu with 5 course, or you can create your own 3, 4, or 5 course meal from the selection of items on the right side of the menu. The awesome ptart? You don't have to choose one item per each section (ie. appetizers, main course, dessert, etc). Personally, I know dessert is a big thing here, but i'm not a major dessert person so I ordered 1 appetizer, 2 seafood, and 1 meat dish. I opted for the 4 course meal and the bf got the 3 course meal. Per the waiter, they cater your meal and the size/portion of each dish pending on how many courses you end up ordering. This way, you're not overly stuffed by the time that giant strawberry souffle comes to the table. Now onto the food: -Seared foie gras with caramelized onions over a bed of greens: dear lord this was heaven. I can't explain how buttery and soft this dish was. It was literally, possibly, one of the best experiences i've ever had in my month. This is a must have. -oysters in some sort of sauce (under appetizers): very delicately flavor oysters flavored in a green broth. Good, light appetizers to start off with. -Soft Shell crab (seasonal), tempura style: surprisingly flavorful batter and well marinade crab. Compared to the ones I'm use to ordering in a Japanese restaurant, this little crab was tangy and sweet in flavor. I appreciated that they took the time to really infused the crab with flavor and season the batter. -Seared Scallops: Another MUST ORDER in my opinion if you love seafood. The scallops were seared to perfection, so plump, and aromatic. This was delicious. -Bison: this was a miss for me. I personally was not a fan of this this...too lean ( i know bison is lean) and i didn't like the gnocci(?) that it was served with. Will pass on this one IMO. -Pork Belly: umm..this was to die for. OMG, the pork belly was so tender, it surpasses the pork belly you would get from momofuku in new york pork buns! -Strawberry Souffle: soft and pillowy, if you like dessert, then this is a good option that isn't too sweet. great sauce served table side to increase the "coolness" of the dish. Overall, an amazing experience. Of course, service was superb. You're definitely not going to have an empty water glass here. The waiters were also super helpful in providing detailed information on the menu. I would love to come back for another celebratory occasion in the future.

Where do I even begin?? Ok, let's see, my absolute favorite dish here was the seared foie gras! The foie was ridiculously juicy and flavorful, literally every single bite melted in my mouth. The caramelized onions and apples added the perfect amount of sweetness to this savory dish! My second favorite item here was the lobster with potato purée! I also added white truffle shavings onto it and you would love this if you're a fan of truffles. The lobster was tender and the potato purée was seasoned perfectly! Next on my list is the crispy farm egg with grits and I'm usually not a fan of grits, so this is saying a lot! I think the best thing about this place is that they can make any ordinary food like grits taste so good! For dessert, we ordered the flambéd bananas. They bring out a cart and make them right in front of you - dessert AND a show! This dessert was so simple but so good! The only thing I would like is more ice cream to go with it. Overall, I had one of the best meals ever and I wanna come back again and try their other dishes! One I have my eye on already is the chocolate soufflé!

What. a. treat. My friends wanted to take me to my first fine dining and chose Gary Danko. For $300 for 2 people I genuinely expected better. Especially after the thousands of 5 star reviews. I was super looking forward to coming here for months and I finally made a reservation that wasn't at 9 or 10. I came here with the boyfriend for our 3 year anniversary. I ordered the 5 course, he ordered the 4 because he didn't want dessert. I had: Foie Gras Risotto Lobster Duck Breast Creme Bruelee. Bf had: Poached egg Seared beef Venison Pork Loin The foie gras was good. I haven't had foie gras in years and it hit a really nice spot. I can do without the cooked pears on the plate. The risotto was extremely creamy and there was more seafood in it than I was anticipating. Not really sure what the hype was though, maybe I'm just not a big risotto fan. The lobster was the most disappointing entree. I was expecting a big lobster tail, instead what I got was half a super tiny lobster. The duck breast was the best of the two entrees. Cooked medium rare. Portion sizes were super tiny. I was genuinely still hungry even after the 3rd course. The duck was the most filling. My boyfriend had 3 courses of nothing but meat and he was jokingly asking "McDonalds?" However, I will have to admit, their meat is cooked to perfection. I had a bite of my boyfriends entrees and none of the meat was chewy. The sauce on the seared beef and venison just tasted... brown. I got the creme brulee for dessert but I think I should have gotten the pineapple upside down cake. The tableside flambee made me regret my dessert choice. There were 3 creme brulees, a .. vanilla? a hazelnut chocolate, and then something something bourbon. The vanilla had a really bitter sugar coating that made the whole thing unenjoyable. The hazelnut chocolate was good but it was too sweet. I had a small bite of the bourbon and I thought it was the most disgusting thing I put into my mouth. This one wasn't properly set and the consistency was soupy. It tasted like burnt caramel. It didn't taste awful but the texture put me way off. For our anniversary, they brought out an extra chocolate dessert, and that was extremely nice of them. Service was meh. I was expecting more. There were a rotation of 5 men. The most attentive of them all were the one who came and served us bread. And he stopped coming when we said we didn't want anymore bread. They stopped by in our entire 2 hour meal to refill our water once. Every other time was just to take our plates away and set new ones. The thing that ruined the meal wasn't any of the food but my coke. My boyfriend and I don't drink so I'll order a coke at any restaurant I go to. I ordered a coke at the beginning when we sat down and finished it after my first appetizer course. The coke came in a small high ball glass that was half glass. When it was empty, nobody came over and asked me if I wanted a refill for a good 20 minutes. Someone finally asked if I wanted another beverage and I said coke, and he 's like another one? And I'm like yes please. When I finished my second coke, the staff just let the empty glass sit there. When the bill came, I saw that we were charged 2 cokes at $4 each. I mean, compared to the $250 meal that's nothing... but I mean COME ON. WHAT RESTAURANT DOES THAT? I've gone to nicer restaurants like John Howie that sells $160 steaks that don't do that. I've gone to restaurants that just comp the soda because it costs them a quarter. IT'S A COKE. SERVED IN A 8OZ HIGH BALL GLASS THAT WAS HALF ICE. How does that warrant $4, and being charged PER GLASS? I mean I understand if it was some cheap Asian restaurant that just dumps a can of coke at my table and expect me to pour it myself over ice. This wasn't even like... special coke. It was watered down coke in a tiny small glass. I just honestly can't get over that. I'm still angry.

I don't know why I haven't Yelp about Gary Danko but they deserve 5 stars for sure! I have been coming here regularly around once every month or two. Every time I am at Gary Danko, the service is always at its best and the food quality never fails to my satisfaction. What I recommend before coming is to be sure to make a reservation at-least 2 weeks ahead because they tend to get a little busy on the weekends and especially during the holiday season. My favorite dish here will probably be their seared foie gras... it's just the texture is so perfect along with the caramelized sauce the chef makes...simply perfection. For my seafood choices here, I always end up with their seared scallops or their maine lobster dish because it's just too good that draws me to always pick one of them. For desserts, if you are a chocolate lover like me- be sure to pick their chocolate soufflé (those take about 20-25 minutes to prepare) so order at the start of your meal. Also, valet services is offered at the front of the restaurant for $20.

I say close to 3.5 stars. This restaurant been in SF for years and didn't come here prior because they had a coat requirement, but now, they don't so here we come. Michelin one star and do give it that you can pick 3 to 5 course dinner and there is a selection of food choices for everyone. So, for those picky eaters, this may be a place to take them for something fancy. I got the 4 course and it was good food and basic, nothing really creative or blew my mind. In short: Pricy but worth every penny. You really pay for an experience (that includes Michelin star food) when you come to Gary Danko. Long Version: I took my mom here for her birthday dinner. She, like most moms, is a very particular person who likes everything to be just so. In terms of food, she can be ridiculously picky and our food tastes have often clashed in the past, so I knew dinner was no small feat. I had to find a place with a large, flexible menu so both of us could enjoy. Across the menu though, there had to be ubiquitous high quality and tastiness, because no one wants to be the sad person at dinner coveting someone else's plate. For all her pickiness, my mom also LOVES food, so the quantity had to be decent- no giant plates with 3 grains of rice and a milligram of sauce for her! And then there's the experience- atmosphere, service, plating and place settings, etc.- which also had to be both elegant and fun. Overall, after several weeks of research, all signs pointed to Gary Danko. I've been disappointed in the past, so I simply told my mom that we were going to a decently nice dinner and made sure to secure a reservation. However, from the moment we walked in, there were good signs- it was lively and bustling at 8PM on a Monday, people were smiling, we were seated immediately in a booth (which I had requested). From turning the table to accommodate us sliding into the booth, to refiling bread plates immediately, to friendly authentic conversations with the wait staff about the menu, to subtly slipping me my mother's birthday present (which I had forgotten at my apartment and had my friend drop off half way through the dinner), the service was sublime down to the smallest detail. And now for the food... our amuse bouche was a lobster and mint salad topped with a watermelon gazpacho. It was literally a summery party for our tastebuds! It was complex but perfectly balanced. The juxtaposition of textures and flavors tipped us off to the fact that a treat was in store. I could wax on for ages about how each dish was familiar in its ingredients but a wonderful experience in terms of flavor. The presentation each time was sublime and somehow each dish impressed us with its levels of intricacy. Seeing as we each had 4 unique courses though, I'm just going to say what we had and admonish you to trust the recommendations. All of the dishes were rich with flavor and beautifully presented and you need not worry about picking the "wrong" dish. My meal: - Sautéed Chesapeake Bay Soft Shell Crab with Oven Dried Tomato, Braised Bacon, Romaine and Boursin Cheese - Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive and Port Roasted Figs - Seared Filet of Beef with Potato Gnocchi, Olive Oil, Swiss Chard and Stilton Butter - Lemon Soufflé Cake with Crème Fraîche Panna Cotta and Raspberry Sorbet My mom's meal: - Pan Seared Scallops with Morel Mushrooms, English Peas and Madeira - Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Candied Peanuts and Shiitake Mushrooms - Roasted Pork Tenderloin and Belly with Champagne Braised Savoy Cabbage, Maitake Mushrooms and Fingerling Potatoes - Crème Fraiche Cheesecake with Strawberry Rhubarb Compote, Crème Anglaise and Strawberry Sorbet After our dessert they brought out a special little chocolate mousse cake with "Happy Birthday" written in chocolate on the rim of the plate. The cake was absolutely scrumptious and after that came a platter of small desserts and 2 breakfast cakes to-go. Could they have thought of anything else?! This place is truly special and definitely worth the extra money. Things to keep in mind: - Your chances of getting a reservation, especially last minute, are infinitely higher if you call. The process is slightly annoying but it's worth it. - You don't have to get one of each course. One of the best part of Gary Danko in my opinion is that you really do get to craft your own wonderful tasting experiences. So, if you want, get 5 courses of desserts- no one's going to force you into cheeses. - Ask for a wine recommendation. Even if you think you know the art of pairing or you're only getting one glass, get the sommelier's input. They consistently let you taste the wine before buying so worst case scenario, you get to try a new wine and you'll know you were right. But let me stress the intricacies of most of the dishes here. This is not your normal duck or average lobster. - Unless you're a cheese lover to the max, skip the cheese course. Paying $20-$30 for a couple bites of nicely displayed cheeses is NOT worth it in comparison to the works of art the chefs create. If you're really craving specialty cheeses, go to a fromagerie or gourmet food instead. - If you eat the bread off of your plate, the servers WILL give you more bread. While in small pieces, this bread is quite filling. DO NOT let if ruin your appetite.

This restaurant really lives up to its name! The menu is superb and offers a great selection. For being a Michelin star restaurant, the price is really not bad! $128 for a five course meal and you can pick any 5 courses off their extensive menu! The place is very happening and easy to get a reservation too!

    I want to start this review by admiring the ambiance Gary Danko has to offer. Upon entry, my guests and I were greeted by the hosts and seated promptly. Their menu offers a variety of dishes, 3+ course meals.

    The night of our dinner, Gary Danko was featuring the Truffle Tasting menu. The options were endless! The truffled risotto with rock shrimp, dungeness crab, shimeji mushrooms and root vegetables was my favorite of the evening. It had rich flavors all around, and the crab and shrimp really complemented the dish. My second favorite entree was the branzini, the emulsified saffron-orange added an artistic touch to this dish as it was very presentable. The fish was crispy on the outside, while tender and flavorful within. I finished my meal with the recommended lemon soufflé cake, which was paired with a refreshing raspberry sorbet.

    My guests enjoyed the venison, lamb, and filet. I sampled the lamb and it was delicious! I found the blend of medoojl dates and farroto quite interesting (and tasty, nonetheless). In addition to the lemon soufflé cake, we ordered the chocolate and pumpkin soufflé. Both were exceptional, although I don't think I would overindulge. Their wine list definitely deserves a look over. I really enjoyed the french chardonnay over dinner.

    Gary Danko is a fine American restaurant. It presents its guests with hospitality and a traditional dining experience.

    Gary Danko is one of my favorite restaurants in San Francisco. If I had more money, I would come here all the time. Truthfully though, as far as nicer Michelin starred restaurants in the Bay Area go, Gary Danko is really good value. The service is impeccable as well.

    At Gary Danko, you choose how many courses you'd like and pay accordingly (3 Courses: $87, 4 Courses: $106, 5 Courses: $124). In my opinion, the prices are all pretty reasonable since the portion sizes are on the more generous side too. In addition to having the flexibility of choosing how many courses you want, you get the flexibility of choosing what the courses are as well. If your heart desires that all 5 of your courses come from their Fish and Seafood section, your heart will get what it wants. I do need to advise that you reserve one of your 3+ courses to be the seared foie gras. Their seared foie gras is not only delicious but also quite a good size. Pretty much everything is delicious though, so you can't really go wrong.

    Gary Danko has been on my to-try list forever, but alas, I kept postponing it for all the exciting new restaurants cropping up. First world dining problems. When I finally visited, I went in with expectations of an old school, but strong fine dining menu, and stellar service. The food met my expectations for 1 Michelin star, but the service fell short.

    FOOD:
    Gary Danko offers a tasting menu or a pick-your-own 3, 4, or 5 course menu. Our table went the custom route, and they even let us choose varying course lengths. Half our table skipped dessert, and one got an extra entree, but the timing was such that it wasn't awkward.

    Oysters w/ Caviar - A staple dish. Better than I expected. Creamy, decadent, with a strong oyster taste.

    Seared Sea Scallops - Perfectly cooked, tender scallops. Nice contrast with the crunchy lotus root chip.

    Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb - Not the best plating, but the lamb was juicy and had delicate flavor. Went well with the polenta.

    Coconut Thai Curry w/ Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Shiitake - This was one loaded dish with at least two of each seafood ingredient. The curry was delicious, but I'm easy to please with Thai curry. The plating was also messy, but it evoked a rustic feel.

    Cheese Course - This was my favorite course by far. You pick from a glorious cheese cart display! On top of that, they had a goat cheese called "Adrienne." Match made in heaven? We chose four cheeses each, served with grapes and bread. Of the four, I actually liked Adrienne the least! But that's because the other three (including the best blue cheese I've had) were outstanding. Mmm mmm.

    Roasted Pear over Gingerbread w/ Nutmeg Ice Cream - I loved the flavors of the nutmeg ice cream and the gingerbread. The pear wasn't bad, but it didn't add to the other components.

    SERVICE:
    Gary Danko service is legendary and many would say that it outshines the food. Perhaps we came on an off-night, because I was seeing cracks in the seemingly perfect service. Water took just a tad longer to be refilled, my empty cocktail glass stayed on my table for 20+ min, servers waited too long to check-in, etc. The killer was when we just got into our car at the valet and the server came running out, check in hand. "I gave you the wrong check!" We asked if it was more or less. Of course we owed more. The waiter even said "Yeah, I'm really glad I caught up with you guys." Tacky tacky.

    AMBIANCE:
    Upscale, white glove atmosphere. Many male diners wearing suit jackets. Very dark inside, even when it was sunny outside.

    Other notes:
    -Total dinner time was just under 3 hours.
    -Parting gift was a very moist and tasty pumpkin cheese cream muffin.
    -Some of the nicest restaurant bathrooms I've seen. Absurdly soft toilet paper.

    2/27/2017

    Numerous reviews stating the obvious - great food & wine choices, great service, great ambiance, and great location.  Let me reconfirm and reinforce the obvious.

    Food - as a diner you have many options.  Set tasting menu, 3-4-5 course options and the entire party can pick and choose as they please without all being forced to select the same courses.  Wine parings also to match each individual course if you choose so.  For appetizer we loved the Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar and Seared Foie Gras.  For seafood, go with the Sea Bass and for poultry, the Stuffed Quail.  The Bison, is less fatty than beef, thus you will need to go medium rare and be ready to work the mandible.  The Grand Marnier Soufflé is fluffy, rich, baked goodness with two sauces and scoop of ice cream.  Baked good packed for the next morning or for a late night snack.

    Service - professional, knowledgable, un-pretentious service.  Our Wait Team consisted of Sam, Jeremiah (Sommelier), William, and Neal.  Sam and William described the menu and dining format.  They also suggest plate presentation if you order multiple items in the same category.  Usually from lighter to heavier fare.  Jeremiah described each wine paring with passion and also helped recharge a cell phone when my son mentioned his photo shooting phone was almost out of power.  The wine parings were described in great detail with each course and the pours were generous.  Neal supplied bread constantly, cleared plates, and snapped pictures for us.  All around great service and the staff is perceptive as to when patrons want minimal to additional dialog.

    Ambiance - beautiful Asian themed setting with orchids and cherry blossoms interspersed throughout the restaurant.  Tables are a bit close together but not to the point where other diners' conversations are disruptive.  Place was constantly packed - a good sign.

    Location - a block away from Ghiradelli Square, walking distance to some of the best views of San Francisco Bay, valet parking, and free street parking after 6pm if you have time to look for a space.

    Gary Danko is a great three-hour value.

    My first Michelin star experience, and it sure was a good one. Thank you BF for surprising me and making a reservation for our anniversary. I was truly surprised not only by our reservation, but also the presentation and execution of the food, and of course, world class service. Coming in on a friday night, we made a reservation, showed up early and was seated promptly. FYI: Valet is approx $20. We were able to find street parking 2 blocks away..so if you don't mind walking.

    If you haven't read the copious amount of reviews, Gary Danko works like this: you cane either choose a prefix menu with 5 course, or you can create your own 3, 4, or 5 course meal from the selection of items on the right side of the menu. The awesome ptart? You don't have to choose one item per each section (ie. appetizers, main course, dessert, etc). Personally, I know dessert is a big thing here, but i'm not a major dessert person so I ordered 1 appetizer, 2 seafood, and 1 meat dish.

    I opted for the 4 course meal and the bf got the 3 course meal. Per the waiter, they cater your meal and the size/portion of each dish pending on how many courses you end up ordering. This way, you're not overly stuffed by the time that giant strawberry souffle comes to the table.

    Now onto the food:
    -Seared foie gras with caramelized onions over a bed of greens: dear lord this was heaven. I can't explain how buttery and soft this dish was. It was literally, possibly, one of the best experiences i've ever had in my month. This is a must have.

    -oysters in some sort of sauce (under appetizers): very delicately flavor oysters flavored in a green broth. Good, light appetizers to start off with.

    -Soft Shell crab (seasonal), tempura style: surprisingly flavorful batter and well marinade crab. Compared to the ones I'm use to ordering in a Japanese restaurant, this little crab was tangy and sweet in flavor. I appreciated that they took the time to really infused the crab with flavor and season the batter.

    -Seared Scallops: Another MUST ORDER in my opinion if you love seafood. The scallops were seared to perfection, so plump, and aromatic. This was delicious.

    -Bison: this was a miss for me. I personally was not a fan of this this...too lean ( i know bison is lean) and i didn't like the gnocci(?) that it was served with. Will pass on this one IMO.

    -Pork Belly: umm..this was to die for. OMG, the pork belly was so tender, it surpasses the pork belly you would get from momofuku in new york pork buns!

    -Strawberry Souffle: soft and pillowy, if you like dessert, then this is a good option that isn't too sweet. great sauce served table side to increase the "coolness" of the dish.

    Overall, an amazing experience. Of course, service was superb. You're definitely not going to have an empty water glass here. The waiters were also super helpful in providing  detailed information on the menu.

    I would love to come back for another celebratory occasion in the future.

    In short: Pricy but worth every penny. You really pay for an experience (that includes Michelin star food) when you come to Gary Danko.

    Long Version:
    I took my mom here for her birthday dinner. She, like most moms, is a very particular person who likes everything to be just so. In terms of food, she can be ridiculously picky and our food tastes have often clashed in the past, so I knew dinner was no small feat.

    I had to find a place with a large, flexible menu so both of us could enjoy.  Across the menu though, there had to be ubiquitous high quality and tastiness, because no one wants to be the sad person at dinner coveting someone else's plate.  For all her pickiness, my mom also LOVES food, so the quantity had to be decent- no giant plates with 3 grains of rice and a milligram of sauce for her! And then there's the experience- atmosphere, service, plating and place settings, etc.- which also had to be both elegant and fun.

    Overall, after several weeks of research, all signs pointed to Gary Danko. I've been disappointed in the past, so I simply told my mom that we were going to a decently nice dinner and made sure to secure a reservation. However, from the moment we walked in, there were good signs- it was lively and bustling at 8PM on a Monday, people were smiling, we were seated immediately in a booth (which I had requested).

    From turning the table to accommodate us sliding into the booth, to refiling bread plates immediately, to friendly authentic conversations with the wait staff about the menu, to subtly slipping me my mother's birthday present (which I had forgotten at my apartment and had my friend drop off half way through the dinner), the service was sublime down to the smallest detail.

    And now for the food... our amuse bouche was a lobster and mint salad topped with a watermelon gazpacho. It was literally a summery party for our tastebuds! It was complex but perfectly balanced. The juxtaposition of textures and flavors tipped us off to the fact that a treat was in store. I could wax on for ages about how each dish was familiar in its ingredients but a wonderful experience in terms of flavor. The presentation each time was sublime and somehow each dish impressed us with its levels of intricacy.  Seeing as we each had 4 unique courses though, I'm just going to say what we had and admonish you to trust the recommendations.  All of the dishes were rich with flavor and beautifully presented and you need not worry about picking the "wrong" dish.

    My meal:
    - Sautéed Chesapeake Bay Soft Shell Crab with Oven Dried Tomato, Braised Bacon, Romaine and Boursin Cheese
    - Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive and Port Roasted Figs
    - Seared Filet of Beef with Potato Gnocchi, Olive Oil, Swiss Chard and Stilton Butter
    - Lemon Soufflé Cake with Crème Fraîche Panna Cotta and Raspberry Sorbet

    My mom's meal:
    - Pan Seared Scallops with Morel Mushrooms, English Peas and Madeira
    - Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Candied Peanuts and Shiitake Mushrooms
    - Roasted Pork Tenderloin and Belly with Champagne Braised Savoy Cabbage, Maitake Mushrooms and Fingerling Potatoes
    - Crème Fraiche Cheesecake with Strawberry Rhubarb Compote, Crème Anglaise and Strawberry Sorbet

    After our dessert they brought out a special little chocolate mousse cake with "Happy Birthday" written in chocolate on the rim of the plate. The cake was absolutely scrumptious and after that came a platter of small desserts and 2 breakfast cakes to-go.  Could they have thought of anything else?! This place is truly special and definitely worth the extra money.

    Things to keep in mind:
    - Your chances of getting a reservation, especially last minute, are infinitely higher if you call. The process is slightly annoying but it's worth it.

    - You don't have to get one of each course. One of the best part of Gary Danko in my opinion is that you really do get to craft your own wonderful tasting experiences. So, if you want, get 5 courses of desserts- no one's going to force you into cheeses.

    - Ask for a wine recommendation. Even if you think you know the art of pairing or you're only getting one glass, get the sommelier's input. They consistently let you taste the wine before buying so worst case scenario, you get to try a new wine
    and you'll know you were right.  But let me stress the intricacies of most of the dishes here. This is not your normal duck or average lobster.  

    - Unless you're a cheese lover to the max, skip the cheese course. Paying $20-$30 for a couple bites of nicely displayed cheeses is NOT worth it in comparison to the works of art the chefs create. If you're really craving specialty cheeses, go to a fromagerie or gourmet food instead.

    - If you eat the bread off of your plate, the servers WILL give you more bread. While in small pieces, this bread is quite filling. DO NOT let if ruin your appetite.
